<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-241-155 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 813 269</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Jan 18 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Texas Instruments lays off 725.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Buckler, Grant.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Texas Instruments Inc. (Layoffs).andO;Ticker:    TXN.andO;Topic:     Computer industryLayoffDefense Contracts.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>****TEXAS INSTRUMENTS LAYS OFF 725 01/18/91 DALLAS, TEXAS, U.S.A., 1991 JAN18 (NB) -- It almost sounds like a joke, but employees at Texas Instrumentsprobably weren't laughing.andP;  On the day the shooting started in the PersianGulf, the company announced it would lay off 725 workers in the UnitedStates, blaming persistent weakness in the defense industry.andM;More than two thirds of the cuts came in TI's Defense Systems and ElectronicsGroup.andP;  However, the Information Technology and Semiconductor groups werealso affected, with cuts of 125 and 60 jobs respectively.andP;  Terri West, a TIspokeswoman, said no programs in those groups will be dropped as a result ofthe cuts, noting that the reductions represent a fairly small percentage ofthe staff in each area.andM;West said that despite the Gulf war, TI expects no upturn in defense spendingany time soon.andP;  &quot;It's really too early to speculate as to what impact warmight have,&quot; she said, but she added that so far, defense contractors are notexpecting a major increase in their business.andM;All of the cuts are in the United States, West said.andP;  They affect workers atTI's North Texas operations as well as some in Tennessee, Colorado, andCalifornia.andP;  All the layoffs took effect Wednesday, West said.andP;  She saidthose who lost their jobs will get at least 60 days' severance pay andinsurance benefits, and added that TI is providing outplacement services,including an outplacement center in Dallas.andM;(Grant Buckler/19910118/Press Contact: Terri West, Texas Instruments,214-995-2984)</TEXT></DOC>